description.en:
It is strongly recommended that every resource that should be rendered to an end user have at least one name.
Different types of name can be distinguished using classifications.
See: https://linked.art/model/base/#names

Arches note: This node's content should be the value for the title descriptor function, when used for a resource model.

* BranchId: la-name

It is strongly recommended that every resource that should be rendered to an end user have at least one name.
Different types of name can be distinguished using classifications.
See: https://linked.art/model/base/#names

Arches note: This node's content should be the value for the title descriptor function, when used for a resource model.

In many cases, current data does not support the level of specificity that the full ontology allows, or the information is simply best expressed in human-readable form. For example, instead of a completely modeled set of parts with materials, many museum collection management systems allow only a single human-readable string for the "medium" or "materials statement".  Any time that there is a description of the resource, with or without qualification as to the type of description, then this branch can be used to record the descriptive text.
See: https://linked.art/model/base/#statements-about-a-resource

* BranchId: la-statement
